ce:section.ce:para:
Similar to the catalytic activity of enzymes [35], the pH value, temperature and H2O2 concentration might affect the catalytic activity of CDs@Fe3O4. In order to study their effects on the catalytic activity of CDs@Fe3O4, we measured the catalytic activity of CDs@Fe3O4 by changing the pH value from 1 to 11, the temperature from 10 to 60 °C, and the H2O2 concentration from 10 to 55 mM. The optimal pH value and temperature for CDs@Fe3O4 were approximately 3.8 and 40 °C, respectively, which were very similar to the HRP (Fig. 3
                        ). Thus, we adopted pH 3.8 and 40 °C as the standard conditions for the subsequent analysis of the CDs@Fe3O4 activity. Moreover, the catalytic activity of CDs@Fe3O4 increased with the concentration of H2O2 and reached the maximum activity at 33.5 mM. Meanwhile, the optimal condition of Fe3O4 was investigated. As shown in Fig. 4
                        , Fe3O4 nanoparticles exhibited the highest activity when the pH was set as 3.8, which was similar to that of CDs@Fe3O4. However, the optimal H2O2 concentration was 60 mM, which was higher than that of CDs@Fe3O4. These results indicated that the peroxidase-like activity of CDs@Fe3O4 was higher than that of Fe3O4 nanoparticles.
